4c681049601b3c374f1d2c0077c99049: I don't want to do intersection, no 4c681049601b3c374f1d2c0077c99049: I just want to see if el.style.WebkitTransform = 'blah'; will actually fire a el.addEventListener('webkitTransitionEnd') 2cdd7064b290132617248dbfd85f740e: if it's not going to transition, I need to call a callback right then 4c681049601b3c374f1d2c0077c99049: that's not the issue 4c681049601b3c374f1d2c0077c99049: -webkit-transform is transitionable 0de37da1d654c10aed33d7b7347b8e3b: if it's to the same value it doesn't fire a transition ok, tiny bit more context to move between apps / most visited on Chrome's NTP we use -webkit-transform: translate3d(-1579px, 0, 0); and to do it animatedly, we add -webkit-transition: -webkit-transform 200ms; if we have a no-op movement (which we can have) I'd like to know if there will actually be a transitionEnd as the method I'm creating has a callback that needs to be fired when you're on the correct page so doing a 0s transition doesn't help and when you set the .WebkitTransform it modifies the style so I don't really want to trust that i.e. .WebkitTransform = 'translate3d(-157px, 0, 0)' -> 'translate3d(-157px, 0px, 0px)' well, I might have to not do this but it brought up a bigger question of telling if this was possible for any property, not just this case I'm really looking for a generic way to tell if a webkitTransitionEnd will fire 2cdd7064b290132617248dbfd85f740e: can you even cancel? 8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: Why would postMessage() not be useful for communicating with other windows? That use case makes sense to me (send messages on onload()) - I guess the intent of postMessage() is that the behavior is undefined if you are sending it to another window while that window's content is still loading? 8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: Sure. a question heh why is it that WebGL needs TypedArray but canvas 2D context does not? what's different about that 3D api that requires binary support? ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c - I see, thanks I think it would be good for vlad to consider adding that as informative background to the Introduction section of the TypedArray spec le it would seem like something that did not rely on sniffing would be preferable so, whitelist of MIME types OK, so that type playing devil's advocate for architectural-purity/sanity advocates: I guess I would suggest that you bail yeah but I guess they are not so rare enough to have not cause serious problems in the past e.g., like that Apache default being to treat everything as text/plain even it if doesn't have a MIME type in general for new specs it seems like the most sane thing for interop is being as unforgiving as possible and keep the option open of adding forgiveness later I wonder if the Typed Arrays spec draft is the first to ever include a section explicitly titled with "Bikeshedding" regardless, I like it. So I hope it starts a trend so does it seem like browser implementors are going to be satisfied with the Typed Arrays spec as a binary-data API in general (rather than just specifically for the WebGL case)?

The only large arrays in the 2D context are pixel arrays, which are just arrays of octets and therefore easy 3D needs large arrays of floats (vertex coordinates), shorts (vertex array indices), etc and large arrays of different types interleaved (so each array element can encode all the data for a vertex)

yeah, ImageData is in fact a typed array it's just that you don't need more than that I think any fallback behavior is ok as long as it's defined whether that is hard fail or some kind of sniffing the interop problem is mainly if you don't define it which is why so much video still gets served as text/plain the more kinds of resources get sniffed, the harder it is to verify that the full set of sniffing algorithms does not have holes therefore I would advocate not doing sniffing for new kinds of formats if there isn't a deep need for it (and by "holes" I mean opportunity to make things get sniffed multiple ways to create a security hole)

On the other hand, the inflexibility required by simplicity conflicts with the goal of being deployable without large-scale content changes. But realistically, you're not going to get XSS protection without doing drastic things like banning inline script, so maybe deployability needs to be deemphasized. Basically, it seems like when the issue is "you should design an API for this", the decision process is extremely ill-suited, as it requires people to bundle up the "I think this is an area we should cover" with a specific API design.
